{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491340"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:43:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:43:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"915"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/915"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.53,0.22,0.07,0.02,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"915"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86364"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/915"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"915"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70642"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"329"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"2084"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3348"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3433"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29630"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29656"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45891"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86364"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of intermittent, uncomfortable swelling under the left side of his jaw. The swelling is more noticeable during and after eating. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The left submandibular gland is enlarged but soft and nontender. Bimanual palpation of the floor of mouth reveals no palpable calculi.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound","Sialogram","Computed tomography","Fine needle aspirate","Intraoral X-ray"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms highly suggestive of sialolithiasis - a submandibular mass that fluctuates with meals. Sialolithiasis most commonly affects the submandibular gland due to its tortuous duct anatomy and more viscous secretions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is now considered the preferred initial investigation for suspected sialolithiasis. It has several key advantages: it is non-invasive, does not use ionising radiation, is readily available in most settings, and has high sensitivity (\u0026gt;90%) for detecting calculi. It can identify stones as small as 2mm and can visualise both radiopaque and radiolucent calculi. Ultrasound also allows real-time assessment of gland function and can detect secondary changes such as ductal dilatation or parenchymal changes. Additionally, it can help exclude other pathology such as masses, lymphadenopathy, or inflammatory conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESialogram\u003C/strong\u003E provides excellent anatomical detail of the ductal system and is particularly useful for surgical planning if intervention is required. However, it is more invasive, requires contrast administration which can be painful, and is generally reserved as a second-line investigation after ultrasound confirmation. It may also be contraindicated during acute infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography\u003C/strong\u003E can identify calculi and provide detailed anatomical information but involves radiation exposure and is typically reserved for complex cases or when malignancy is suspected. It is also more expensive and less readily available than ultrasound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspirate\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there was concern for neoplasia, but is not indicated as an initial investigation when the history is typical for sialolithiasis. It is invasive and does not provide information about ductal anatomy or calculi.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntraoral X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E can detect radiopaque calculi but will miss radiolucent stones (about 20%). It provides limited information about gland architecture and is less commonly used now that ultrasound is widely available. The sensitivity is also operator-dependent and anatomical superimposition can make interpretation challenging.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ultrasound is the preferred initial investigation for suspected sialolithiasis due to its safety, accessibility, and high sensitivity (\u003E90%)","A fluctuating submandibular mass that worsens with eating is highly suggestive of sialolithiasis","Sialogram provides detailed anatomical information needed for surgical planning but is not first-line"],"references":["Bova R. A guide to salivary gland disorders. MedicineToday. 2006;7(2):44-48. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9061151/#:~:text=Salivary%20gland%20disorders%20may%20be,tumors%20of%20the%20salivary%20glands.","Kim DH, Kang JM, Kim SW, Kim SH, Jung JH, Hwang SH.Laryngoscope. 2022 Sep;132(9):1785-1791. doi: 10.1002/lary.30020. Epub 2022 Jan 19.","Badash I, Raskin J, Pei M, et al. (August 18, 2022) Contemporary Review of Submandibular Gland Sialolithiasis and Surgical Management Options. Cureus 14(8): e28147. doi:10.7759/cureus.28147"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70642"}},"question":{"data